## 7. Code Quality & Testability — 10 pts

> Inspired by **Test-Driven Development** principles: every behavior should be provable by a test; code should be structured so that components are independently verifiable.

| Criterion | Excellent (9–10) | Good (7–8) | Adequate (5–6) | Poor (0–4) |
|-----------|------------------|------------|-----------------|------------|
| **Modularity** | Code is organized into clear, independently testable modules (e.g. `detector.py`, `recognizer.py`, `database.py`, `gui.py`). Functions have single responsibilities. | Reasonable separation but some monolithic sections. | Everything in one or two files; hard to isolate components. | Spaghetti code with no structure. |
| **Automated tests** | Unit tests exist for key functions (embedding generation, similarity scoring, threshold logic, database CRUD). Tests are runnable via a single command (e.g. `pytest`). | Some tests present but incomplete coverage. | No automated tests; only manual verification described. | No tests of any kind. |
| **Reproducibility** | `requirements.txt` or Conda `environment.yml` provided; clear README with setup and run instructions; seeds set for deterministic behavior where applicable. | Dependency list provided; basic instructions. | Dependencies listed informally (e.g. in comments). | No dependency info; cannot reproduce setup. |

